"Sham J.F.C., Lo T.Y., Xu W.T.","Continuous Surface Temperature Monitoring to estimate sensible heat loss by building finishes",2011,"Environmental Engineering and Management Journal","10","2",,"311","317",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-80052441334&partnerID=40&md5=683754909da2e569eb78e112440f17cc","City University of Hong Kong, Department of Building and Construction, Tat Chee Avenue, Kowloon Tong, Hong Kong","Sham, J.F.C., City University of Hong Kong, Department of Building and Construction, Tat Chee Avenue, Kowloon Tong, Hong Kong; Lo, T.Y., City University of Hong Kong, Department of Building and Construction, Tat Chee Avenue, Kowloon Tong, Hong Kong; Xu, W.T., City University of Hong Kong, Department of Building and Construction, Tat Chee Avenue, Kowloon Tong, Hong Kong","This paper proposes a novel technique, Continuous Surface Temperature Monitoring (CSTM), that uses infrared technology to estimate the sensible heat (SH) transfer between building finishes materials and the surrounding environment without knowing the physical and thermal properties of the tested materials. It is critical to study the contribution of heat transferred by building fabrics to the Urban Heat Island (UHI) effect because of the increasing threat of global warming. One method to investigate this is to measure the SH loss of building fabrics. Its magnitude is the product of object's mass, m, its specific heat, c, and its temperature change, ΔT. In this study, CSTM estimates the cooling curves of four building finishes tiles: concrete, marble, clay, and ceramic. The results are quite satisfactory in that there is only 11.86% error between the SH calculated by the formal Sensible eat equation (mcΔT) and the CSTM technique. The study also shows that clay tiles have the highest SH loss per unit volume to the surrounding environment, and the optimal parameter settings for the technique are discussed.","Continuous temperature measurement; Infrared technology; Sensible heat; Urban heat island effect",,,,,,,"ASHRAE Handbook (2005) ASHRAE Handbook: Fundamentals, , American Society of Heating, Refrigerating and Air-Conditioning Engineers, Atlanta, Ga; Bahadori, M.N., Haghighat, F., Weekly storage of coolness in heavy brick and adobe walls (1985) Energy and Buildings, 8, pp. 259-270; Berdahl, P., Bretz, S.E., Preliminary survey of the solar reflectance of cool roofing materials (1997) Energy and Buildings, 25, pp. 149-158; Bonacquisti, V., Casale, G., Palmieri, S., Siani, A., A canopy layer model and its application to Rome (2006) Science of the Total Environment, 364, pp. 1-13; Bretz, S.E., Akbari, H., Long-term performance of high-albedo roof coatings (1997) Energy and Buildings, 25, pp. 159-167; Bruse, M., Fleer, H., Simulating surface-plant-air interactions inside urban environments with a threedimensional numerical model (1998) Environmental Modelling and Software, 13, pp. 373-384; Chudnovsky, A., Ben-Dor, E., Saaroh, H., Diurnal thermal behaviour of selected urban objects using remote sensing measurements (2004) Energy and Buildings, 36, pp. 1063-1074; Ciutina, A., Tuca, I., Ungureanu, V., Dubina, D., Design of buildings including environmental impact (2010) Environmental Engineering and Management Journal, 9, pp. 1121-1131; Giridharan, R., Ganesan, S., Lau, S., Daytime urban heat island effect in high-rise and high-density residential developments in Hong Kong (2004) Energy and Buildings, 36, pp. 525-534; Hafner, J., Kidder, S., Urban heat island modeling in conjunction with satellite-derived surface/soil parameters (1999) Journal of Applied Meteorology, 38, pp. 448-465; Hartz, D., Prashad, L., Hedquist, B., Golden, J., Brazel, A., Linking satellite images and hand-held infrared thermography to observed neighborhood climate conditions (2006) Remote Sensing of Environment, 104, pp. 190-200; Holt, T., Pullen, J., Urban canopy modeling of the New York city metropolitan area: A comparison and validation of single and multilayer p